About me

Curiosity is the thread that ties together my love for science, code, and strategy. As a Master’s student in Computational Biology with a specialization in Computer-Aided Drug Design, I am driven by a simple yet ambitious goal: to decode biology through computation and bring innovative solutions to healthcare.

What fascinates me most is the space where biology meets technology. Whether it’s designing peptide inhibitors for neurodegenerative diseases or simulating protein dynamics, I thrive on using computational tools to tackle complex biological questions. My work dives deep into epigenetics, proteomics, genomics, and structural biology—fields that I see not just as academic domains but as frontiers waiting to be explored.

Over the years, I’ve had the chance to work on diverse, hands-on projects:

  • Predicting protein structures and docking interactions

  • Writing Python scripts for statistical analysis and molecular simulations

  • Building machine learning models for pattern recognition

  • Mapping evolutionary relationships using MEGA

  • Studying residue-level dynamics with DSSP

But beyond the lab and code, I’m a gamer. Strategy games fuel my mind the same way research does—they demand foresight, creativity, and the ability to solve problems under pressure. That mindset spills into my programming: I’m always tweaking tools, testing limits, and looking for smarter ways to do things.

For me, science is not just about knowledge—it’s about discovery. Every project is a new quest, every dataset a puzzle, and every insight a step closer to changing the way we understand life. I'm here to be part of that change.

Looking Forward: I am eager to collaborate with professionals on groundbreaking Bioinformatics projects where teamwork and innovation thrive.
